title: For Sale:  High Standard Military Victor Target 22
postcontent: Here is a fantastic, dead accurate, High Standard Military Victor, made in Hamden, Connecticut in 1974. This gun has had two owners. The original owner was a USA Olympic marksman. He set it up with two barrels, a scope, and custom grips.The original Matched High Standard Victor barrel is unmodified with the vented rib from the factory. The second barrel is a NAPCO Barrel, marked with its own serial number. The NAPCO barrel has an ADCO Solo Red Dot scope / sight mounted on it.In addition to both barrels, and the red dot scope, this comes with both its original High Standard checkered walnut thumb rest grips and a pair of Randall Fung custom made Match Grips.It also comes with an extra 10 round magazine (for a total of two magazines), and a High Standard box that is in great shape.I am the second owner. I bought this because I like nice things and I wanted an accurate 22 to teach my children with. I owe the set up of the extra barrel, the scope, the custom grips, and the extreme care this pistol has had to the original owner. He upgraded the trigger to a target / match / competition trigger.I can vouch for its accuracy. It is amazing. But I didn't enter any competitions or win anything, except for the admiration and attention of others at the range.I have never used the original barrel. I only used the NAPCO one with the scope on it. I did take the other out of the safe twice a year and oiled it.I am selling this simply because it doesn't get used any more. It has always been way above my level of ownership. I'm not a collector. I'm a guy who likes nice guns and who takes them out 2-3 times a year (I wish I went more, but most years its less) to shoot them. This one went out when my kids were young, but it has sat in the safe for maybe 10 years. It's time to sell it.My loss is your gain. The barrels look mirror clean to me. I tried to capture every flaw in pictures. It is a beautiful gun. Its serial number is #2434099. You can see that in the pictures. The box is correct as to what gun it is. But I am not sure why the serial number on the box does not match. I think I mixed up boxes at some point. At one time I had four of these High Standard Victors. I sold two years ago. I kept this one because it was always the nicest. I still do have one other. It's a plunker that I'm keeping because it is not worth much.I have this listed with more pictures on Gunbroker. Here is the link - https://www.gunbroker.com/item/732679208  Email me any questions. Thanks for looking!

postcontent:
The Model 700 CDL “Boone and Crockett” Series – celebrates America’s most successful bolt-action, centerfire rifle and one of the country’s oldest and most important conservation organizations, the Boone and Crockett Club®. This hunting rifle is a 300 Win Mag and is recognized for its legendary performance and accuracy, the Model 700 has a rigid, cylindrical receiver design that adds stiffness and a solid bedding area for the action in the stock. A counterbored bolt face encloses the cartridge head with an unbroken ring of steel, which then fits inside of the barrel chamber, surrounded by the receiver – creating the famous Remington “three-rings-of-steel.” This time-proven design creates an action of unparalleled strength. With this solid construction and advanced design, the Model 700 has earned a reputation for its out-of-the-box accuracy.
The Model 700 CDL “Boone & Crockett” Series provides that same renowned accuracy and reliability in a classically styled, well-designed package. Housed in a straight comb, brown laminate stock with right-handed cheek piece, black fore-end tip and grip cap, this Model 700 defies the elements and provides the hunter a solid platform he can depend on in any weather. The rifle wears a fluted carbon steel barrel 26-inch barrel, with receivers drilled and tapped for ease of mounting optics. Both barrel and action wear an attractive, non-reflective satin blued finish. A jeweled bolt body completes the classic look of these centerfire rifles.
The hinged floorplate magazine has a three round capacity. Fit with a patented Remington recoil pad, even the unwelcome “punch” of the high-powered magnum is significantly diminished. This high performance rifle also has the X-Mark Pro™ fire control system that delivers crisp, perfect trigger pulls with virtually no creep and come set at three to five pounds from the factory. An attractive medallion featuring the B & C logo is inset into the grip cap and “Boone & Crockett” is laser engraved into the barrel, recognizing this most American of conservation organization.
